WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.437 --> 00:00:05.271
One of the most infamous

00:00:05.305 --> 00:00:07.440
psychological studies
ever conducted

00:00:07.473 --> 00:00:10.376
was the Stanford Prison
Experiment.

00:00:10.409 --> 00:00:13.646
It's mentioned in almost every
intro to psychology textbook.

00:00:13.679 --> 00:00:17.316
They tend to focus on
how unethical it was,

00:00:17.349 --> 00:00:20.687
and are less critical
of its supposed conclusion.

00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:24.323 line:0%
<i> August 14th, 1971.</i>

00:00:24.356 --> 00:00:25.758 line:0%
<i> Palo Alto, California.</i>

00:00:25.791 --> 00:00:29.162
<i> Twelve young men are rounded
 up from their homes by police,</i>

00:00:29.195 --> 00:00:30.496
<i> placed under arrest,</i>

00:00:30.529 --> 00:00:32.065
<i> and brought to
 a makeshift prison</i>

00:00:32.098 --> 00:00:34.767
<i> in the basement
 of Stanford University.</i>

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:37.737
<i> It all begins as a study on
 the psychology of prison life,</i>

00:00:37.770 --> 00:00:41.441 line:0%
<i> led by Stanford psychology
 professor Dr. Philip Zimbardo.</i>

00:00:41.474 --> 00:00:43.076 line:0%
<i> 24 volunteers--</i>

00:00:43.109 --> 00:00:45.812
<i> 12 guards
 and 12 prisoners.</i>

00:00:45.845 --> 00:00:47.713
<i> --have agreed to spend
 the next two weeks</i>

00:00:47.746 --> 00:00:50.650
<i> recreating life
 in a correctional facility.</i>

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:55.822 line:0%
[guard]

00:00:55.855 --> 00:00:58.691 size:84% position:58% line:0%
<i> The prisoners are booked
 and stripped nude.</i>

00:00:58.724 --> 00:00:59.992
<i> They're no longer
 individuals,</i>

00:01:00.026 --> 00:01:03.729
<i> forced to wear smocks,
 stocking caps and shackles.</i>

00:01:03.762 --> 00:01:05.765
<i> Identified only by
 their prisoner numbers.</i>

00:01:13.405 --> 00:01:15.675 size:84% position:58% line:0%
<i> The guards quickly adapt
 to their new profession.</i>

00:01:15.708 --> 00:01:18.344
<i> Given anonymity by
 their mirrored sunglasses,</i>

00:01:18.377 --> 00:01:21.647
<i> some of them start to control
 the meager food rations,</i>

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:23.583
<i> restrict prisoners'
 bathroom use.</i>

00:01:23.616 --> 00:01:25.518
<i> And, as tensions rise,</i>

00:01:25.551 --> 00:01:27.220
<i> so do their cruel methods.</i>

00:01:36.428 --> 00:01:39.332
<i> Within just six days
 of the planned two-week study,</i>

00:01:39.365 --> 00:01:40.700
<i> conditions are so bad</i>

00:01:40.733 --> 00:01:43.269
<i> that the entire operation
 is shut down.</i>

00:01:43.302 --> 00:01:44.838 line:0%
[man]

00:01:47.540 --> 00:01:49.275 line:0%
Goddamn it...

00:01:49.308 --> 00:01:51.511
<i> The study makes international
 headlines.</i>

00:01:51.544 --> 00:01:52.846
<i> Zimbardo's fame skyrockets,</i>

00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:55.848
<i> and his conclusions are taught
 to students worldwide,</i>

00:01:55.881 --> 00:01:58.417
<i> used as a defense
 in criminal trials</i>

00:01:58.450 --> 00:01:59.618
<i> and are even submitted
 to Congress</i>

00:01:59.651 --> 00:02:02.688
<i> to explain the abuses
 inflicted at Abu Ghraib.</i>

00:02:02.721 --> 00:02:04.490
<i> The study brings up
 a question</i>

00:02:04.523 --> 00:02:07.293
<i> just as important then
 as it is today:</i>

00:02:07.326 --> 00:02:10.329
<i> is evil caused
 by the environment,</i>

00:02:10.362 --> 00:02:11.931
<i> or the personalities in it?</i>

00:02:11.964 --> 00:02:14.200
<i> Zimbardo's shocking conclusion</i>

00:02:14.233 --> 00:02:16.335
<i> is that when people
 feel anonymous</i>

00:02:16.368 --> 00:02:18.771
<i> and have power over
 depersonalized others,</i>

00:02:18.804 --> 00:02:20.940
<i> they can easily become evil.</i>

00:02:20.973 --> 00:02:24.710
<i> And it occurs more often
 than we'd like to admit.</i>

00:02:24.743 --> 00:02:27.613
But while it's true that people
were mean to each other

00:02:27.646 --> 00:02:29.682
during the Stanford
Prison Experiment,

00:02:29.715 --> 00:02:32.518
what if what truly caused
that behavior

00:02:32.551 --> 00:02:35.622
wasn't what we've always
been told?

00:02:53.839 --> 00:02:55.374
<i> The Stanford Prison Experiment</i>

00:02:55.407 --> 00:02:57.510
<i> has always had
 its controversies.</i>

00:02:57.543 --> 00:02:59.312
<i> But a wave of recent
 revelations</i>

00:02:59.345 --> 00:03:01.314
<i> have pushed it back
 into the spotlight</i>

00:03:01.347 --> 00:03:02.682
<i> 47 years later.</i>

00:03:02.715 --> 00:03:05.484
<i> Today, I'm going to speak
 with journalist Ben Blum,</i>

00:03:05.517 --> 00:03:07.420
<i> whose recent writings
 have brought criticism</i>

00:03:07.453 --> 00:03:09.488
<i> of the experiment
 to a larger audience</i>

00:03:09.521 --> 00:03:10.722
<i> than ever before.</i>

00:03:10.756 --> 00:03:13.926
How did you get involved in
the Stanford Prison Experiment

00:03:13.959 --> 00:03:15.695
in the first place?

00:03:15.728 --> 00:03:18.798 size:88% position:56% line:0%
Well, my involvement
was quite personal.

00:03:18.831 --> 00:03:21.500
Like everyone,
I had kind of absorbed

00:03:21.533 --> 00:03:23.769
the basic lesson
of the experiment

00:03:23.802 --> 00:03:25.938 size:84% position:42%
through the cultural ether.

00:03:25.971 --> 00:03:28.841
And then my cousin Alex
was arrested for bank robbery.

00:03:28.874 --> 00:03:33.646
This was a team of mostly
military guys with AK-47s.

00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:34.814
Alex was the driver.

00:03:34.847 --> 00:03:37.450
He was a 19-year-old
U.S. Army Ranger.

00:03:37.483 --> 00:03:39.852
And it was a superior of his
on the Rangers

00:03:39.885 --> 00:03:41.421
that organized and led
the bank robbery.

00:03:42.988 --> 00:03:45.591
Alex thought the whole thing
was a training exercise.

00:03:45.624 --> 00:03:49.562
He was just so brainwashed
in this intense Ranger training

00:03:49.595 --> 00:03:53.399
that when a superior proposed
this bank robbery,

00:03:53.432 --> 00:03:57.804
he took it as just one more kind
of tactical thought experiment.

00:03:59.772 --> 00:04:02.341
Then Dr. Philip Zimbardo
participated

00:04:02.374 --> 00:04:04.277
in his legal defense.

00:04:04.310 --> 00:04:08.014
Zimbardo submits a letter
to the court,

00:04:08.047 --> 00:04:10.816
advocating leniency
in sentencing on the grounds

00:04:10.849 --> 00:04:14.387
that Alex, my cousin,
had been so transformed

00:04:14.420 --> 00:04:17.990
by the social environment
of the Ranger battalion

00:04:18.023 --> 00:04:20.626
that he participated
in the bank robbery

00:04:20.659 --> 00:04:23.763
without exercising
his own free will.

00:04:23.796 --> 00:04:25.931
Well, how did that affect
Alex's sentencing?

00:04:25.964 --> 00:04:30.469
He received an extraordinarily
lenient sentence of 16 months.

00:04:30.502 --> 00:04:34.507
So Zimbardo was a family hero.

00:04:34.540 --> 00:04:37.910
But over time, Alex,
finally he did admit to me,

00:04:37.943 --> 00:04:40.046
you know what, I knew this was
a bank robbery by the end,

00:04:40.079 --> 00:04:42.381
and I just didn't have the moral
courage to back out.

00:04:42.414 --> 00:04:43.683
Oh, wow.

00:04:43.716 --> 00:04:46.585
Alex, myself and our
whole family

00:04:46.618 --> 00:04:50.089
came to view
the Zimbardo argument

00:04:50.122 --> 00:04:54.660
as a way to shirk personal
culpability,

00:04:54.693 --> 00:04:58.998
and to put all the blame
on the situation.

00:04:59.031 --> 00:05:00.599
So you start looking

00:05:00.632 --> 00:05:03.803
at the Stanford Prison
Experiment in particular.

00:05:03.836 --> 00:05:06.372
You reached out to Dr. Zimbardo
himself,

00:05:06.405 --> 00:05:08.574
as well as some of those
who participated.

00:05:08.607 --> 00:05:10.343 align:start size:59% position:41%
What did you learn?

00:05:10.376 --> 00:05:13.512 size:63% position:31%
I learned,
to my deep surprise,

00:05:13.545 --> 00:05:16.482 align:start position:0%
that quite a number
of the participants

00:05:16.515 --> 00:05:20.986
had stories of their experience
that completely contradicted

00:05:21.019 --> 00:05:21.887 align:start position:0%
the official narrative.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:25.591
Which is, look,
these regular people,

00:05:25.624 --> 00:05:26.959
good people,
came together,

00:05:26.992 --> 00:05:30.629
and because of the situation,
became evil.

00:05:30.662 --> 00:05:32.365
[Ben]
Right.

00:05:32.398 --> 00:05:34.700
Zimbardo has claimed
that the guards

00:05:34.733 --> 00:05:36.102
were put in the situation,

00:05:36.135 --> 00:05:39.739
and then the kind of hidden
wellspring of sadism

00:05:39.772 --> 00:05:41.674
that apparently lies
in all of us

00:05:41.707 --> 00:05:43.609
unfolded organically.

00:05:43.642 --> 00:05:45.778 align:start size:56% position:44% line:0%
[Zimbardo]

00:05:54.186 --> 00:05:56.956
There was an orientation meeting
for the guards.

00:05:56.989 --> 00:06:00.393
They had been told
quite explicitly

00:06:00.426 --> 00:06:02.362
to oppress the prisoners.

00:06:03.796 --> 00:06:05.898 size:88% position:56% line:0%
That falls under the heading
of what psychologists call

00:06:05.931 --> 00:06:07.800 line:0%
demand characteristics.

00:06:07.833 --> 00:06:09.668 line:0%
Experimental subjects
tend to be motivated

00:06:09.701 --> 00:06:12.705 line:0%
to give experimenters
what they want.

00:06:12.738 --> 00:06:14.073
[Michael]
<i> Demand characteristics occur</i>

00:06:14.106 --> 00:06:16.108
<i> whenever participants
 being studied</i>

00:06:16.141 --> 00:06:18.043
<i> act differently
 than they normally would</i>

00:06:18.076 --> 00:06:21.046
<i> because they've guessed
what hypothesis is being tested</i>

00:06:21.079 --> 00:06:24.984
<i> and feel that a certain kind
 of behavior is being demanded.</i>

00:06:25.017 --> 00:06:28.788
There was a recording
of explicitly correcting a guard

00:06:28.821 --> 00:06:31.524
who wasn't being tough enough.

00:06:58.917 --> 00:07:00.553
So a conclusion
you could make

00:07:00.586 --> 00:07:02.721
from the Stanford
Prison Experiment

00:07:02.754 --> 00:07:05.458
is that when you tell people
to be cruel,

00:07:05.491 --> 00:07:07.059
they'll do it if you tell them

00:07:07.092 --> 00:07:09.061 size:75% position:63%
it's for a greater good,
like science.

00:07:09.094 --> 00:07:10.195
-Right.
-Who would have thought?

00:07:10.229 --> 00:07:15.968
I think the study stands still
as a fascinating spur

00:07:16.001 --> 00:07:18.237
to further more careful research

00:07:18.270 --> 00:07:21.240
as a demonstration that should
make anyone curious

00:07:21.273 --> 00:07:24.877
as to how such extreme behavior
could arise

00:07:24.910 --> 00:07:26.111 align:start position:0%
in such a short time.

00:07:26.144 --> 00:07:29.748
The experiment could still
be useful,

00:07:29.781 --> 00:07:31.717
but it might need to be
reinterpreted.

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:34.520
Its data might lead
to different conclusions

00:07:34.553 --> 00:07:36.889
than the one that we've been
telling for so many decades.

00:07:36.922 --> 00:07:38.458
Right.

00:07:39.691 --> 00:07:41.560
<i> The flaws in the experiment</i>

00:07:41.593 --> 00:07:43.262 line:0%
<i> that Ben and other critics
 bring up</i>

00:07:43.295 --> 00:07:45.664 size:81% position:59% line:0%
<i> call into question large
 portions of the narrative</i>

00:07:45.697 --> 00:07:47.566
<i> surrounding the study.</i>

00:07:47.599 --> 00:07:50.803
<i> So I want to hear from someone
 who was actually there.</i>

00:07:59.177 --> 00:08:02.047 line:0%
<i> Dave Eshelman, the study's
 most infamous guard,</i>

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:05.284 align:end size:91% position:91% line:0%
<i> agreed to tell me
 his side of the story.</i>

00:08:05.317 --> 00:08:07.019 size:63% position:31%
It's really an honor
to meet you.

00:08:07.052 --> 00:08:11.524
You're a living, walking piece
of psychology history.

00:08:11.557 --> 00:08:13.859
I'm never recognized in the
street or anything like that,

00:08:13.892 --> 00:08:16.295
although I still get
some hate mail.

00:08:16.328 --> 00:08:18.163
-Are you serious?
-Yeah, absolutely.

00:08:18.196 --> 00:08:20.900
Well, what do you say to them
when they react that way?

00:08:20.933 --> 00:08:23.969
I say, well, there's probably
a lot about that

00:08:24.002 --> 00:08:27.740
that didn't happen quite the way
it's been portrayed.

00:08:27.773 --> 00:08:29.241
Well, Dave,
before we go too far,

00:08:29.274 --> 00:08:31.644
I'd like to watch the footage
we have here

00:08:31.677 --> 00:08:34.113
so we can kind of talk about
what we see.

00:08:36.048 --> 00:08:37.049
[Dave]
That's me there, by the way.

00:08:37.083 --> 00:08:39.285
-[Michael] Look at that look.
-[Dave] Mm-hmm.

00:08:39.318 --> 00:08:43.789
So how did you get involved with
a Stanford Prison Experiment?

00:08:43.822 --> 00:08:46.625 size:78% position:61%
My father was a professor
at Stanford,

00:08:46.658 --> 00:08:49.929 align:end position:100%
and I was home for summer,
looking for a summer job.

00:08:49.962 --> 00:08:52.131
So I'm looking
through the want ads.

00:08:52.164 --> 00:08:53.232
$15 a day.

00:08:53.265 --> 00:08:56.769
You know,
in 1971 that wasn't bad.

00:08:56.802 --> 00:08:58.938
The way it was introduced
to the guards,

00:08:58.971 --> 00:09:01.307
the whole concept
of this experiment,

00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:03.275
we were never led to believe

00:09:03.308 --> 00:09:06.579
that we were part
of the experiment.

00:09:06.612 --> 00:09:08.747 size:69% position:66%
We were led to believe
that our job

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:11.250
was to get results
from the prisoners,

00:09:11.283 --> 00:09:12.952
that they were the ones
the researchers

00:09:12.985 --> 00:09:14.320
are really studying.

00:09:17.856 --> 00:09:19.959
The researchers
were behind the wall.

00:09:19.992 --> 00:09:21.760
And we all knew
they were filming.

00:09:21.793 --> 00:09:23.362
And we can often hear
the researchers

00:09:23.395 --> 00:09:26.298
commenting on the action
from the other side of the wall.

00:09:26.331 --> 00:09:28.267
You know, like,
"Oh, gosh, did you see that?

00:09:28.300 --> 00:09:30.202
Here. Make sure you get
a close-up of that."

00:09:30.235 --> 00:09:36.141
Okay? So if they want to show
that prison is a bad experience,

00:09:36.174 --> 00:09:37.109
I'm going to make it bad.

00:09:37.142 --> 00:09:39.211
But how did you feel
doing stuff like that?

00:09:39.244 --> 00:09:40.245
Didn't you feel bad?

00:09:40.279 --> 00:09:41.480
I don't know if this
is a revelation to you,

00:09:41.513 --> 00:09:45.117
but 18-year-old boys are not
the most sensitive creatures.

00:09:45.150 --> 00:09:47.319
-Sure.
-My agenda was to be

00:09:47.352 --> 00:09:49.622
the worst guard
I could possibly be.

00:09:49.655 --> 00:09:51.624
-And it's pretty serious.
-Mm-hmm.

00:09:57.396 --> 00:10:01.066
This is my favorite part
of all the footage we have

00:10:01.099 --> 00:10:02.768
-from the experiment.
-Mm-hmm.

00:10:02.801 --> 00:10:06.038
It's you and a prisoner
confronting each other

00:10:06.071 --> 00:10:08.807
after the experiment.

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:10.943
I remember the guy saying,
"I hate you, man."

00:10:10.976 --> 00:10:12.612
-Yeah.
-"I hate you."

00:10:38.437 --> 00:10:42.841
Each day I said, well,
what can we do to ramp up

00:10:42.874 --> 00:10:43.809
what we did yesterday?

00:10:43.842 --> 00:10:45.411
How can we build on that?

00:10:45.444 --> 00:10:47.312
Why did you want
to ramp things up?

00:10:47.345 --> 00:10:48.113
Two reasons, I think.

00:10:48.146 --> 00:10:50.783
One was because
I really believed

00:10:50.816 --> 00:10:55.087
I was helping the researchers
with some better understanding

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:57.156
of human behavior.

00:10:57.189 --> 00:10:58.023
On the other hand,

00:10:58.057 --> 00:11:00.259
it was personally
interesting to me.

00:11:00.292 --> 00:11:04.697
You know, I cannot say that I
did not enjoy what I was doing.

00:11:04.730 --> 00:11:08.400
Maybe, you know,
having so much power

00:11:08.433 --> 00:11:11.303
over these poor,
defenseless prisoners,

00:11:11.336 --> 00:11:15.207
you know, maybe you kind of
get off on that a little bit.

00:11:15.240 --> 00:11:19.878
You weren't entirely following
a script from a director.

00:11:19.911 --> 00:11:21.080
Right.

00:11:21.113 --> 00:11:22.981 align:start position:0%
But you also felt like

00:11:23.014 --> 00:11:25.751
Zimbardo wanted something
from you.

00:11:25.784 --> 00:11:27.486
-Yes.
-And you gave that to him.

00:11:27.519 --> 00:11:29.221
I believe I did.
I think I decided

00:11:29.254 --> 00:11:31.356
I was going to do a better job
than anybody there

00:11:31.389 --> 00:11:33.992
of delivering
what he wanted.

00:11:34.025 --> 00:11:36.495
But does that excuse me
from what I was doing?

00:11:36.528 --> 00:11:39.865
Certainly it started out
with me playing a role.

00:11:39.898 --> 00:11:43.435
So the question is, was there
a point where I stopped acting

00:11:43.468 --> 00:11:45.838
and I started living,
so to speak?

00:11:49.775 --> 00:11:53.278
The standard narrative is that
Dave Eshelman did what he did

00:11:53.311 --> 00:11:55.247
because when people
are given power,

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:58.851
it's easier than we think
for abuse to happen.

00:11:58.884 --> 00:11:59.852
That may be true,

00:11:59.885 --> 00:12:03.822
but how predisposed
to aggression was Dave?

00:12:03.855 --> 00:12:05.390
I mean, he signed up
to something called

00:12:05.423 --> 00:12:07.993
a "prison study," after all.

00:12:08.026 --> 00:12:11.964
Also, his feeling
that cruelty was encouraged

00:12:11.997 --> 00:12:16.034
and helped the experiment,
may have affected his behavior.

00:12:16.067 --> 00:12:17.936
What I'd like to see is,

00:12:17.969 --> 00:12:19.972
in the absence
of outside influence,

00:12:20.005 --> 00:12:25.010
can anonymity, power,
and depersonalization alone

00:12:25.043 --> 00:12:27.179
lead to evil?

00:12:27.212 --> 00:12:28.514
<i> To answer that question,</i>

00:12:28.547 --> 00:12:29.815
<i> I'd like to design</i>

00:12:29.848 --> 00:12:31.383
<i> a demonstration of my own.</i>

00:12:31.416 --> 00:12:33.152
<i> So I'm meeting
 with Dr. Jared Bartels</i>

00:12:33.185 --> 00:12:34.853
<i> of William Jewell College,</i>

00:12:34.886 --> 00:12:36.922
<i> a psychologist who has written
 extensively</i>

00:12:36.955 --> 00:12:38.824
<i> about the Stanford
 Prison Experiment</i>

00:12:38.857 --> 00:12:40.459
<i> and how it is taught.</i>

00:12:40.492 --> 00:12:45.498
I would love to do the Stanford
Prison Experiment again.

00:12:46.031 --> 00:12:48.967 size:81% position:41% line:0%
You could probably make it
more ethical,

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:50.435
but still find the same
conclusions.

00:12:50.468 --> 00:12:52.204
That's my hypothesis.

00:12:52.237 --> 00:12:53.839
I absolutely think
it's worthwhile.

00:12:53.872 --> 00:12:55.808
It's important.
It's interesting.

00:12:55.841 --> 00:12:57.009
Probably the best approach

00:12:57.042 --> 00:13:01.513
is eliminate as best as possible
the demand characteristics

00:13:01.546 --> 00:13:04.950
by eliminating that
prisoner/guard dynamic.

00:13:04.983 --> 00:13:07.119
Why do we even need to call one
group "guards"

