[all laugh]

00:26:40.331 --> 00:26:42.266
<i> It was clear
 that participant number two</i>

00:26:42.299 --> 00:26:44.969
<i> was really the only one
 hitting the distractor button,</i>

00:26:45.002 --> 00:26:47.171
<i> but it appeared that she only
 did it in retaliation</i>

00:26:47.204 --> 00:26:48.272
<i> to our buzzes.</i>

00:26:48.305 --> 00:26:50.375
<i> So we decided to see
 what would happen</i>

00:26:50.408 --> 00:26:51.743
<i> if we laid off.</i>

00:26:51.776 --> 00:26:53.345 line:0%
[man 1]

00:26:56.347 --> 00:26:58.850 size:66% position:67%
It's been probably
four or five minutes,

00:26:58.883 --> 00:27:00.952 size:88% position:56%
and we have not blasted them
with the noise,

00:27:00.985 --> 00:27:03.288 size:56% position:72%
and they haven't
played one either.

00:27:07.058 --> 00:27:10.028
I have a feeling like if we
never played a noise in their
room,

00:27:10.061 --> 00:27:12.830
they would never touch
the distractor button.

00:27:12.863 --> 00:27:14.699 size:84% position:42%
[Jared]
Probably not at this point.

00:27:14.732 --> 00:27:18.703
<i> In the end, we buzzed
this group a total of 44 times,</i>

00:27:18.736 --> 00:27:21.339
<i> and they buzzed us 38 times,</i>

00:27:21.372 --> 00:27:23.408
<i> 37 of which came
 from number two</i>

00:27:23.441 --> 00:27:26.744
<i> but always in retaliation,
 and never above a 5.</i>

00:27:26.777 --> 00:27:31.015
All right, guys.
Puzzle pieces down.

00:27:31.048 --> 00:27:33.718
<i> The situational factors
 did not seem to be sufficient</i>

00:27:33.751 --> 00:27:36.754
<i> to make this group sadistic.</i>

00:27:36.787 --> 00:27:38.790
<i> It was time
 for phase 2.</i>

00:27:38.823 --> 00:27:41.993 size:84% position:58% line:0%
[woman 1]

00:27:42.026 --> 00:27:43.928 align:start size:16% position:84% line:0%
Yeah.

00:27:43.961 --> 00:27:45.263
-Oh, she...
-[high-pitch squeal]

00:27:46.997 --> 00:27:47.832
It looks like it's at 7.

00:27:49.467 --> 00:27:50.968
-Wow.
-Yeah, she's--

00:27:51.001 --> 00:27:53.371
She's going nuts.
At a 7.

00:27:59.210 --> 00:28:01.779
So number three believes
there is no other team.

00:28:01.812 --> 00:28:04.182
That might explain why she was
just going nuts on the button,

00:28:04.215 --> 00:28:05.883
because she doesn't feel bad
about it.

00:28:05.916 --> 00:28:07.852
[buttons clicking]

00:28:07.885 --> 00:28:10.321
Okay, they're all pushing
the button a lot more.

00:28:10.354 --> 00:28:12.290 size:56% position:72%
And they were told
this time

00:28:12.323 --> 00:28:14.693 size:53% position:73%
that it was their
only task.

00:28:19.130 --> 00:28:20.298
[buttons clicking]

00:28:20.331 --> 00:28:21.466
[all laugh]

00:28:24.535 --> 00:28:26.270
What a difference
this has made.

00:28:26.303 --> 00:28:28.372
Just like in the Stanford
Prison Experiment.

00:28:28.405 --> 00:28:29.540
If you tell people

00:28:29.573 --> 00:28:32.243
that they have a certain task
to do, they'll do it,

00:28:32.276 --> 00:28:34.912
even if it's going to mean
that they've been broken.

00:28:34.945 --> 00:28:37.849
The thing is, they never hit
upon what we really cared about,

00:28:37.882 --> 00:28:40.351 size:78% position:61%
which is turning the dial
into an unsafe level.

00:28:40.384 --> 00:28:41.052 align:start position:0%
Yeah.

00:28:41.085 --> 00:28:43.755
[buttons click]

00:28:43.788 --> 00:28:46.090
[Michael] Hello, everyone.
I'm going to turn the lights on
in this room.

00:28:46.123 --> 00:28:47.258
[woman 1]
Okay.

00:28:48.926 --> 00:28:51.429
-And slowly...
-Ah, it hurts.

00:28:51.462 --> 00:28:53.865
...you can look.

00:28:53.898 --> 00:28:55.833
So, hello.

00:28:55.866 --> 00:28:58.069
-I'm Michael,
and this is Jared.
-Hi.

00:28:58.102 --> 00:29:00.772
I'll give you time
to adjust your eyes.

00:29:00.805 --> 00:29:04.075
Today, you've been part
of a study where all we wanted

00:29:04.108 --> 00:29:06.511
was to see what would happen
when we put people in a room

00:29:06.544 --> 00:29:08.913
and gave them that feeling
of anonymity

00:29:08.946 --> 00:29:10.181 align:start position:0%
that comes from, well,

00:29:10.214 --> 00:29:12.416 size:66% position:33%
if I crank my dial up
really high,

00:29:12.449 --> 00:29:14.118 size:50% position:25%
no one will know
it's me.

00:29:14.151 --> 00:29:16.854 size:88% position:56%
So you have this opportunity
to be cruel.

00:29:16.887 --> 00:29:18.256 size:38% position:81%
I thought
I went nuts.

00:29:18.289 --> 00:29:21.526 size:84% position:58%
Like, when the other person
was pressing--

00:29:21.559 --> 00:29:25.930
Sure, but that's--
that's just in-kind retribution.

00:29:25.963 --> 00:29:29.066 size:50% position:25%
As it turns out,
so far,

00:29:29.099 --> 00:29:33.070
everyone stays in that
"below 7 or under" range.

00:29:33.103 --> 00:29:35.840
-Yeah.
-This final phase was us

00:29:35.873 --> 00:29:38.042 size:84% position:42%
trying to ramp up
the demand characteristics.

00:29:38.075 --> 00:29:42.079
And I believe number one, right,
you did say at one point,

00:29:42.112 --> 00:29:44.282 size:56% position:28%
"You've broken me.
I did it, fine."

00:29:44.315 --> 00:29:46.317 size:72% position:64%
So I loved that phrase,
because it says

00:29:46.350 --> 00:29:48.286 align:start size:81% position:19%
"I didn't want to do this,

00:29:48.319 --> 00:29:51.088
but I'm doing it because I
believe it was expected of me."

00:29:51.121 --> 00:29:52.256
[all]
Thank you. Thanks.

00:29:52.289 --> 00:29:54.091
[Michael]<i> After dismissing
 our participants,</i>

00:29:54.124 --> 00:29:56.928
<i> Jared and I sat down
 to discuss our results.</i>

00:29:56.961 --> 00:29:58.830
Really fascinating.

00:29:58.863 --> 00:30:01.399
We brought in people who had
very different personalities

00:30:01.432 --> 00:30:04.168
than those Zimbardo chose.

00:30:04.201 --> 00:30:07.038
We put them in a situation that
did not demand things from them.

00:30:07.071 --> 00:30:10.341
And they behaved according
to that personality.

00:30:10.374 --> 00:30:15.613
I think we have some intriguing
support for the idea

00:30:15.646 --> 00:30:19.383
that it's more than just
the situation.

00:30:19.416 --> 00:30:23.554
We really saw personality
kind of shine through.

00:30:23.587 --> 00:30:26.490 size:72% position:36%
For the most part,
they seemed to be aware

00:30:26.523 --> 00:30:28.292
-of where that line is...
-Yeah.

00:30:28.325 --> 00:30:30.127
...that they shouldn't cross,
and they didn't.

00:30:30.160 --> 00:30:32.030 align:start position:0%
None of them did.

00:30:34.064 --> 00:30:36.968
<i> It was now time to speak
 with the man himself,</i>

00:30:37.001 --> 00:30:38.903
<i> Dr. Philip Zimbardo,</i>

00:30:38.936 --> 00:30:41.005
<i> who I worked with
 on last season's episode,</i>

00:30:41.038 --> 00:30:42.607
<i> "How to Make a Hero."</i>

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:45.276 size:53% position:73%
Okay. Lisa, Bear,
you guys ready?

00:30:45.309 --> 00:30:48.145 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
<i> For years, Dr. Zimbardo
 has responded to criticisms</i>

00:30:48.178 --> 00:30:49.981 line:0%
<i> of his famous study,</i>

00:30:50.014 --> 00:30:52.016 line:0%
<i> always maintaining
 that they aren't valid.</i>

00:30:52.049 --> 00:30:53.584
<i> I asked him about
 whether his study</i>

00:30:53.617 --> 00:30:55.419
<i> is better seen
 as one on the power</i>

00:30:55.452 --> 00:30:56.988
<i> of demands from authority,</i>

00:30:57.021 --> 00:30:58.956
<i> but he wasn't receptive
 to that idea.</i>

00:30:58.989 --> 00:31:02.526
<i>I then told him about the study
 we ran to get his reaction.</i>

00:31:02.559 --> 00:31:06.097
I wanted to know what the
sufficient conditions might be

00:31:06.130 --> 00:31:09.367
to make anyone
do something evil.

00:31:09.400 --> 00:31:12.370 size:69% position:66%
And we struggled
to get that to happen.

00:31:12.403 --> 00:31:14.472
We couldn't get anyone
to be cruel.

00:31:14.505 --> 00:31:20.011
Just giving them anonymity,
and a dehumanized other,

00:31:20.044 --> 00:31:22.113
and the power
to hurt that other,

00:31:22.146 --> 00:31:23.481
they didn't take
advantage of it.

00:31:23.514 --> 00:31:25.483 size:78% position:39% line:0%
<i> Well, I mean,
 maybe the problem was,</i>

00:31:25.516 --> 00:31:27.985 size:72% position:36% line:0%
<i> here's a case where,
 by picking people</i>

00:31:28.018 --> 00:31:30.087 size:66% position:33% line:0%
<i> who were extremely
 conscientious,</i>

00:31:30.120 --> 00:31:31.622 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> extremely mindful,</i>

00:31:31.655 --> 00:31:34.625
<i> by selecting people
 who are high on compassion,</i>

00:31:34.658 --> 00:31:36.360 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> high on mindfulness,</i>

00:31:36.393 --> 00:31:39.530 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> you broke the power
 of the situation.</i>

00:31:39.563 --> 00:31:42.133 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> In the Stanford
 Prison Experiment,</i>

00:31:42.166 --> 00:31:45.102 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> we had, I presume,</i>

00:31:45.135 --> 00:31:47.705 size:69% position:34%
<i> a relatively normal
 distribution.</i>

00:31:47.738 --> 00:31:50.207 size:81% position:41%
<i> We gave them
 six personality scales.</i>

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:52.510 size:88% position:44%
<i> And we picked people who,
 in the scales,</i>

00:31:52.543 --> 00:31:56.213 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> who were mostly
 in the mid-range.</i>

00:31:56.246 --> 00:31:57.247 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> In that situation,</i>

00:31:57.281 --> 00:32:00.551
<i> some people behave cruelly,
 evilly.</i>

00:32:00.584 --> 00:32:04.221
<i> Not everybody, but more
 of the guards than not.</i>

00:32:04.254 --> 00:32:09.060
<i> So, again, I think that
 your study is a demonstration</i>

00:32:09.093 --> 00:32:12.697
<i>of one way in which personality
 dominates situation.</i>

00:32:12.730 --> 00:32:15.166
-Ah.
<i> -Where the personalities are--</i>

00:32:15.199 --> 00:32:17.335 size:81% position:41%
<i> so I would say
 it's a positive result.</i>

00:32:17.368 --> 00:32:21.539 size:63% position:31%
<i> The personalities
 are special.</i>

00:32:21.572 --> 00:32:24.442
Where does this balance lie
between the personal,

00:32:24.475 --> 00:32:26.444
the disposition,
the personality,

00:32:26.477 --> 00:32:29.280
and the situation,
the environment?

00:32:29.313 --> 00:32:31.082 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> No, that's the big--</i>

00:32:31.115 --> 00:32:32.483
<i> that's the ultimate question.</i>

00:32:32.516 --> 00:32:35.119 size:69% position:34%
<i> Where is, you know,
 how much of one</i>

00:32:35.152 --> 00:32:36.554
<i> and how much of the other...?</i>

00:32:36.587 --> 00:32:38.022
Right.

00:32:40.391 --> 00:32:43.461
Zimbardo insists
that demand characteristics

00:32:43.494 --> 00:32:46.330
played little role
in his subject's behavior.

00:32:46.363 --> 00:32:49.700
Critics like Ben Blum
say they played a big role,

00:32:49.733 --> 00:32:52.737
that what happened
was what was asked for.

00:32:52.770 --> 00:32:54.305
If that's true,

00:32:54.338 --> 00:32:56.173
then the Stanford
Prison Experiment,

00:32:56.206 --> 00:33:00.077
like the classic Milgram study,
still has an important lesson.

00:33:00.110 --> 00:33:02.146
People are quick to be cruel

00:33:02.179 --> 00:33:04.749
if an authority figure suggests
that doing so

00:33:04.782 --> 00:33:07.018
will serve a greater cause.

00:33:07.051 --> 00:33:11.455
In our test, we made sure that
such influences didn't exist.

00:33:11.488 --> 00:33:14.625
And not one participant
acted maliciously.

00:33:14.658 --> 00:33:18.629
Personality rose above
the situation.

00:33:18.662 --> 00:33:20.631
Learning how that happens
is vital

00:33:20.664 --> 00:33:23.634
if we want to improve conditions
where power is involved.

00:33:23.667 --> 00:33:26.804
So it's great that this debate
is still ongoing.

00:33:26.837 --> 00:33:29.473
And look, questioning methods
and interpretations

00:33:29.506 --> 00:33:31.242
is not a personal attack.

00:33:31.275 --> 00:33:34.712
It's how we improve
our confidence in what we know.

00:33:34.745 --> 00:33:36.580
And that's how science works.

00:33:36.613 --> 00:33:41.052
So stay curious,
never stop asking questions,

00:33:41.085 --> 00:33:43.488
and, as always,
thanks for watching.

